instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The digital twin is built around the plant’s sensor data stream, which is collected via two inside temperature sensors and one outside temperature sensor. Sensor data are fed into a simulation module that contains two deterministic models: a two‑parameter model (Model A) and a four‑parameter model (Model B). The twin performs online calibration using least‑squares estimation on recent sensor data to update the models. A Kalman‑filter based estimator fuses the measured inside temperature with the modelled heat‑bed temperature to estimate the unmeasured heat‑bed state. Detection of anomalies in the plant behaviour is performed by comparing the real sensor data against the model predictions. The control strategy is implemented on the Raspberry Pi controller and is re‑configured by the twin after calibration and estimation steps. All these components are coordinated by a lightweight runtime located on the same embedded system, which orchestrates data flow between sensors, models, and control logic."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle in the incubation case follows a cyclic process: (1) Model development – creation of a dynamic model (differential‑equation based) that captures the thermal dynamics of the incubator; (2) Integration – embedding the model within the DT framework alongside real‑time sensor data streams; (3) Deployment – coupling the DT to the physical twin (the incubator box, heatbed, fan, sensors) for online operation; (4) Runtime data acquisition – continuous collection of temperature readings via wired or wireless sensors; (5) Calibration – application of calibration algorithms that update model parameters to minimise the residual between prediction and observation; (6) Monitoring and safety checks – execution of monitoring algorithms that evaluate whether the system remains within predefined safety and performance envelopes; (7) Decision and actuation – if violations are detected, either a human operator or an autonomous supervisory controller issues corrective commands to the physical twin; (8) Iteration – the schedule of calibration and monitoring repeats, refining the model and control logic, thereby creating a governance loop that ensures the DT remains an accurate and actionable representation of the PT."
]

